<p><i><b>The End of Faith: Religion, Terror, and the Future of Reason</b></i> (2004) is a book written by <a href="/wiki/Sam_Harris_(author)" title="Sam Harris (author)">Sam Harris</a>, concerning organized religion, the clash between religious faith and rational thought, and the problems of tolerance towards religious <a href="/wiki/Fundamentalism" title="Fundamentalism">fundamentalism</a>.</p>
<p>Harris began writing the book in what he described as a period of "collective grief and stupefaction" following the <a href="/wiki/September_11,_2001_attacks" title="September 11, 2001 attacks" class="mw-redirect">September 11, 2001 attacks</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Adler_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Adler-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The book comprises a wide-ranging criticism of all styles of <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religious</a> <a href="/wiki/Faith" title="Faith">belief</a>.</p>
<p>The book was first published in August 2004, and it was awarded the <a href="/wiki/PEN_American_Center" title="PEN American Center">PEN</a>/Martha Albrand Award for First Nonfiction the following year.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> The paperback edition was published in October 2005. In the same month it entered the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Times_Best_Seller_list" title="New York Times Best Seller list"><i>New York Times</i> Best Seller list</a> at number four, and remained on the list for a total of 33 weeks.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
